  "prompt": "Operator: reduce_sum along last axis (out[i] = sum_j x[i, j]). Input shapes: [32, 4096]; perf shape [32, 4096]. Output shape: [32]. Dtype: float32. Layout: contiguous. Axis: -1 (last axis). Tiling: row_per_core \u2014 distribute the 32 rows across cores via `asc2.range(rows_per_block, unroll_factor=2, parallel=True)`; for each owned row load the full 4096-wide row in one shot (`asc2.load(x_gm, [num_cols], offsets=[row_offset])`) and call `asc2.reduce_sum(row)` so the whole row reduction is a single wide vector op rather than a per-tile accumulation loop; wrap the scalar result as `asc2.full([1, OUT_PAD], s, dtype=row.dtype)` with OUT_PAD=8 (float32 \u2192 8 elements \u00d7 4 bytes = 32-byte alignment) and store at `[row, 0]`. PERF NOTE: unlike elementwise ops, the tile-WIDTH lever is weak for a last-axis reduction \u2014 the row width (4096) is fixed by the problem, so the win comes from (a) keeping the reduction as one wide `asc2.reduce_sum` over the full row instead of a narrow tiled accumulator loop, and (b) spreading rows across all 16 cores (row_per_core); this mirrors the ops-math arch35 reduction tiling (math/reduce_sum/op_host/arch35) which assigns whole rows to cores. Tail: host_pad (padding=8 element scalar pad). Accumulator: float32 (same as dtype). Tolerance: atol=1e-2, rtol=1e-3 against np.sum(x.astype(np.float32), axis=1). Platform: Ascend950PR_9599. Build/run: python3.11 kernel.py -r Model -v Ascend950PR_9599. Evidence: kernel.py (skills-on adds design.md + verification.md).",
